'''''doolally tap''''' noun loosely meaning "camp fever".

==Etymology==
'''Deolali''' was a [[British]] [[army camp]] 100 miles north-east of [[Bombay]] where British soldiers would stay after finishing their [[tour of duty]], to await [[transport]] back to [[Britain]]. These men would often be driven mad by boredom, and so the phrase came about in reference to their apparant condition. The meaning then spread wider to refer to anyone perceived to behave [[eccentrically]].

"doolally" comes from [[anglicising]] "Deolali" and "[[tap]]" comes from a Persian or Urdu word for a [[malarial fever]] (ultimately from [[Sanskrit]] [[tapa]], meaning "heat" or "torment").

By the 1940s this had been widely shortened to just "[[doolally]]", an adjective meaning "[[mad]]" or "[[eccentric]]".

